1
00:00:04,640 --> 00:00:06,078
<i>They'll know everything very soon.</i>

2
00:00:06,109 --> 00:00:07,742
You're leaving? He'll
be here any second.

3
00:00:07,758 --> 00:00:08,891
Tell him I've gone to West Point.

4
00:00:08,925 --> 00:00:10,585
I have to hurry.

5
00:00:11,156 --> 00:00:13,929
- We have to come with you.
- I can barely make it as it is.

6
00:00:13,954 --> 00:00:15,598
If I take you both, he'll catch us.

7
00:00:15,820 --> 00:00:17,154
He needs to think you're innocent.

8
00:00:17,179 --> 00:00:18,414
You don't know anything, understand?

9
00:00:18,439 --> 00:00:20,436
He won't believe me.
He'll have me arrested.

10
00:00:20,470 --> 00:00:21,771
Make him believe you.

11
00:00:21,805 --> 00:00:23,673
This is the only way I
know to keep you safe.

12
00:00:23,707 --> 00:00:26,777
<i>♪</i>

13
00:00:27,811 --> 00:00:29,412
I love you.

14
00:00:29,446 --> 00:00:32,446
<i>♪</i>

15
00:00:35,418 --> 00:00:39,188
General Washington.
Your Excellency. Welcome.

16
00:00:39,222 --> 00:00:42,222
<i>♪</i>

17
00:00:55,238 --> 00:00:57,651
Will he be much longer?

18
00:00:58,441 --> 00:01:00,743
Any moment, I'm... i'm sure.

19
00:01:02,850 --> 00:01:04,124
[floorboards creaking]

20
00:01:04,149 --> 00:01:05,865
Your Excellency.

21
00:01:06,049 --> 00:01:09,049
<i>♪</i>

22
00:01:18,061 --> 00:01:20,396
Ready. Up.

23
00:01:20,430 --> 00:01:22,832
<i>♪</i>

24
00:01:22,866 --> 00:01:25,501
- What is your business?
- Don't shoot.

25
00:01:25,810 --> 00:01:28,168
- Did you know?
- Your Excellency, I...

26
00:01:28,193 --> 00:01:30,840
- Did you know?
- No, no, he wouldn't.

27
00:01:30,874 --> 00:01:32,842
[baby crying]

28
00:01:32,876 --> 00:01:35,876
<i>♪</i>

29
00:01:40,851 --> 00:01:43,435
Who are you?

30
00:01:44,240 --> 00:01:46,255
My name's Benedict Arnold.

31
00:01:46,289 --> 00:01:48,157
I've come to help you win the war.

32
00:01:48,191 --> 00:01:51,227
<i>[music intensifying]</i>

33
00:02:01,972 --> 00:02:03,572
How are they?

34
00:02:03,607 --> 00:02:06,075
Olivia's conked out,
and I just busted Mark

35
00:02:06,109 --> 00:02:08,177
playing that crazy - Violent
video game again.

36
00:02:08,211 --> 00:02:10,780
Thank you so much for having me.

37
00:02:10,814 --> 00:02:13,744
A home - Cooked meal is a rare and
exotic thing in my life these days.

38
00:02:13,769 --> 00:02:15,694
Believe me, It was my pleasure.

39
00:02:15,719 --> 00:02:17,453
You're a professor?

40
00:02:17,487 --> 00:02:20,423
The history and anthropology
of American political movements.

41
00:02:20,457 --> 00:02:22,625
That alone makes you the
most interesting colleague

42
00:02:22,659 --> 00:02:24,460
of Denise's I've ever met. [chuckles]

43
00:02:24,494 --> 00:02:26,762
Ignore her. She's teasing me.

44
00:02:26,797 --> 00:02:29,131
It also makes you the only
colleague I've ever met.

45
00:02:29,166 --> 00:02:31,233
17 years, nada.

46
00:02:31,268 --> 00:02:33,235
Michelle. [laughs]

47
00:02:33,270 --> 00:02:35,371
Hey, I don't ask questions.

48
00:02:35,405 --> 00:02:38,607
And knowing what she
does, I don't want to ask.

49
00:02:38,642 --> 00:02:41,908
But out of the blue, It's,
"make the mustard chicken.

50
00:02:41,933 --> 00:02:43,646
"Lucy Preston's coming over."

51
00:02:43,680 --> 00:02:46,315
Must have some kind of superpower.

52
00:02:46,349 --> 00:02:47,883
What is it?

53
00:02:47,918 --> 00:02:49,585
To be honest, It, uh,

54
00:02:49,619 --> 00:02:51,821
came as a surprise to me too.

55
00:02:53,161 --> 00:02:55,129
[water running]

56
00:03:01,025 --> 00:03:02,965
Your family is lovely.

57
00:03:02,999 --> 00:03:06,383
Thanks. I wanted you to meet them.

58
00:03:06,408 --> 00:03:09,271
But your wife does have a point.

59
00:03:09,306 --> 00:03:10,739
Why did you invite me over?

60
00:03:10,774 --> 00:03:15,411
I've been up most
nights lately worrying.

61
00:03:15,445 --> 00:03:17,146
I know that Rufus talked to you about...

62
00:03:17,180 --> 00:03:18,981
Rittenhouse? Yeah, that's part of it.

63
00:03:19,015 --> 00:03:20,950
And I'm looking into it, believe me.

64
00:03:20,984 --> 00:03:25,187
But what's really been keeping
me awake is your mother.

65
00:03:25,222 --> 00:03:26,489
My mother?

66
00:03:26,523 --> 00:03:30,459
As hard as it must be for
you to remember your sister,

67
00:03:30,494 --> 00:03:32,461
what's worse for me...

68
00:03:32,496 --> 00:03:34,463
is that your mother doesn't.

69
00:03:34,498 --> 00:03:39,000
She had a daughter she
doesn't even know existed.

70
00:03:39,469 --> 00:03:41,537
Before the time machine,

71
00:03:41,571 --> 00:03:44,773
my worst fear was losing them.

72
00:03:45,141 --> 00:03:47,877
Now it's that I could lose them

73
00:03:47,911 --> 00:03:50,179
and not know they were ever here.

74
00:03:50,213 --> 00:03:51,780
I get it, Lucy.

75
00:03:51,815 --> 00:03:55,065
The pressure you must
feel keeping history intact

76
00:03:55,090 --> 00:03:59,135
so more people aren't just... erased.

77
00:04:00,891 --> 00:04:03,200
I want you to do me a favor.

78
00:04:05,395 --> 00:04:07,496
Keep this in the Lifeboat for me.

79
00:04:07,531 --> 00:04:11,166
<i>[pensive music]</i>

80
00:04:11,201 --> 00:04:12,848
What is it?

81
00:04:13,858 --> 00:04:15,551
It's them.

82
00:04:17,551 --> 00:04:22,068
Pictures, photographs, kindergarten art.

83
00:04:22,748 --> 00:04:25,920
It's our life in a disk.

84
00:04:26,850 --> 00:04:31,264
If you come back someday
and they are gone...

85
00:04:33,356 --> 00:04:35,691
promise you'll show it to me

86
00:04:35,725 --> 00:04:38,680
and tell me everything about tonight.

87
00:04:41,197 --> 00:04:45,071
I need to know they existed.

88
00:04:47,437 --> 00:04:49,305
[whispers] Yeah.

89
00:04:57,354 --> 00:05:00,249
It's not... it's not sexist
if I use a woman to beat you.

90
00:05:00,290 --> 00:05:02,708
[chuckles] All right, we gotta go.

91
00:05:02,886 --> 00:05:04,453
[knock at door]

92
00:05:04,487 --> 00:05:06,088
- Pause button.
- Oh, I can pay for it.

93
00:05:06,122 --> 00:05:07,990
I can afford pizza, Rufus.

94
00:05:08,926 --> 00:05:11,190
- Hey.
- Oh, hello, Jiya.

95
00:05:11,215 --> 00:05:13,562
Sorry to intrude.

96
00:05:13,597 --> 00:05:15,731
Glad you two are a thing, by the way.

97
00:05:15,765 --> 00:05:17,766
- What are you doing here?
- I need to speak to him.

98
00:05:17,801 --> 00:05:19,068
Privately, If you don't mind.

99
00:05:19,102 --> 00:05:21,185
Connor, this is her apartment.

100
00:05:21,210 --> 00:05:23,572
Oh, chivalry. Nevertheless.

101
00:05:23,607 --> 00:05:25,307
I won't take long.

102
00:05:25,342 --> 00:05:27,226
It's all right.

103
00:05:32,682 --> 00:05:35,540
- Are you drunk?
- No.

104
00:05:36,019 --> 00:05:39,063
Yes. Slightly.

105
00:05:40,123 --> 00:05:44,540
I ever tell you my mother
used to, uh... clean houses?

106
00:05:44,928 --> 00:05:47,896
I'd watch her wrestle that
octopus of a vacuum cleaner

107
00:05:47,931 --> 00:05:49,732
of hers and I just wanted to help her.

108
00:05:49,766 --> 00:05:52,001
I just... i thought I could
invent a better one than that.

109
00:05:52,035 --> 00:05:54,503
- And so I did.
- Why are you telling me this?

110
00:05:54,537 --> 00:05:57,633
So then came the solar panels...

111
00:05:58,842 --> 00:06:00,509
the cars...

112
00:06:00,543 --> 00:06:01,656
[chuckles]

113
00:06:03,513 --> 00:06:07,449
and the stocks,
investors, the bottom line.

114
00:06:07,484 --> 00:06:11,163
But I didn't want any of that, really.

115
00:06:12,468 --> 00:06:14,765
I just want to turn a wrench,

116
00:06:15,158 --> 00:06:17,593
make my mother's life a little easier.

117
00:06:18,848 --> 00:06:20,529
Like you.

118
00:06:24,701 --> 00:06:26,795
I'm not a bad guy.

119
00:06:29,873 --> 00:06:33,660
I didn't mean to get
you into this so deeply.

120
00:06:34,411 --> 00:06:37,012
If I'd known it would end this way...

121
00:06:37,047 --> 00:06:39,129
End what way?

122
00:06:43,353 --> 00:06:46,789
Rittenhouse knows you've been
tampering with these recorders.

123
00:06:46,823 --> 00:06:49,158
[scoffs] No, I haven't. I...

124
00:06:49,192 --> 00:06:50,984
They know.

125
00:06:51,995 --> 00:06:55,464
So... last chance.

126
00:06:55,498 --> 00:06:59,529
Whatever the next mission
is, record it properly.

127
00:07:00,270 --> 00:07:01,904
If you don't, I can't protect you

128
00:07:01,938 --> 00:07:04,959
or your family anymore.

129
00:07:10,957 --> 00:07:13,091
I really am very sorry.

130
00:07:15,472 --> 00:07:17,100
Good night.

131
00:07:18,955 --> 00:07:21,924
<i>[pensive music]</i>

132
00:07:21,958 --> 00:07:24,958
<i>♪</i>

133
00:07:26,730 --> 00:07:28,664
What was that about?

134
00:07:28,698 --> 00:07:31,400
[phones chiming]

135
00:07:36,372 --> 00:07:37,873
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

136
00:07:37,907 --> 00:07:40,175
Flynn went to September 25, 1780.

137
00:07:40,210 --> 00:07:42,578
Let me guess, just north of Manhattan.

138
00:07:42,612 --> 00:07:45,047
<i>- How'd you know?</i>
- Oh, this is bad.

139
00:07:45,081 --> 00:07:46,715
This is really, really bad.

140
00:07:46,750 --> 00:07:48,117
What would Flynn want in New York City

141
00:07:48,142 --> 00:07:49,490
in the middle of the Revolutionary War?

142
00:07:49,515 --> 00:07:51,253
<i>It's not New York City; it's West Point.</i>

143
00:07:51,287 --> 00:07:52,921
- The Military Academy?
- In 1780,

144
00:07:52,956 --> 00:07:54,723
west Point was just a
fort, but Washington thought

145
00:07:54,758 --> 00:07:56,859
whoever controlled it would win the war.

146
00:07:56,893 --> 00:07:59,061
So what happened on September 25th?

147
00:07:59,103 --> 00:08:01,044
<i>Well, Washington was over at
Benedict Arnold's house for breakfast</i>

148
00:08:01,069 --> 00:08:04,800
when he learned that Arnold was plotting
to give West Point to the British.

149
00:08:04,834 --> 00:08:06,647
And Arnold fled before
Washington got there.

150
00:08:06,672 --> 00:08:07,970
<i>Benedict Arnold, huh?</i>

151
00:08:08,004 --> 00:08:09,805
The guy whose name basically
means "total jerk - Off."

152
00:08:09,839 --> 00:08:12,105
He was Washington's
most brilliant general

153
00:08:12,130 --> 00:08:13,308
and trusted friend.

154
00:08:13,343 --> 00:08:15,778
Yeah, but Arnold's big
plan failed, obviously.

155
00:08:15,812 --> 00:08:17,446
Maybe Flynn wants to help him succeed,

156
00:08:17,480 --> 00:08:18,814
maybe help the British win the war?

157
00:08:18,848 --> 00:08:19,958
[chuckles] Bully for him.

158
00:08:19,983 --> 00:08:21,917
<i>Guys, do you realize
how bad this could be?</i>

159
00:08:21,951 --> 00:08:24,052
George Washington is at West Point

160
00:08:24,087 --> 00:08:25,754
the morning that Benedict Arnold fled.

161
00:08:25,789 --> 00:08:27,489
You think Flynn is trying
to kill George Washington?

162
00:08:27,524 --> 00:08:29,591
I don't know, but I'm on my way.

163
00:08:29,626 --> 00:08:32,327
[whirring]

164
00:08:32,362 --> 00:08:35,063
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

165
00:08:35,098 --> 00:08:37,299
[warbling tone]

166
00:08:42,366 --> 00:08:43,907
[chuckles]

167
00:08:45,642 --> 00:08:48,642
<i>♪</i>

168
00:08:55,785 --> 00:08:59,611
This is it. This is
Benedict Arnold's house.

169
00:08:59,636 --> 00:09:02,837
- Nice digs.
- Arnold had expensive tastes.

170
00:09:02,862 --> 00:09:04,827
He one time spent £1,000,

171
00:09:04,861 --> 00:09:06,428
which would be like $80,000 today,

172
00:09:06,462 --> 00:09:07,519
on one bottle of wine.

173
00:09:07,544 --> 00:09:10,987
- What? Who does that?
- A Grade A douche nozzle.

174
00:09:12,193 --> 00:09:13,992
Come on.

175
00:09:14,485 --> 00:09:16,055
Okay.

176
00:09:17,796 --> 00:09:20,064
So when does Washington show up?

177
00:09:20,089 --> 00:09:21,923
I don't know exactly.

178
00:09:22,307 --> 00:09:23,741
It doesn't look like anyone's here.

179
00:09:23,766 --> 00:09:24,980
Did we miss Flynn?

180
00:09:25,014 --> 00:09:26,682
Maybe he already helped Arnold escape.

181
00:09:26,716 --> 00:09:28,453
Stop!

182
00:09:28,478 --> 00:09:29,818
Don't move!

183
00:09:29,853 --> 00:09:31,687
- We're patriots.
- Quiet!

184
00:09:31,721 --> 00:09:34,223
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

185
00:09:34,257 --> 00:09:36,586
More traitors?

186
00:09:39,492 --> 00:09:41,493
Who are you?

187
00:09:42,055 --> 00:09:44,700
And what the hell are you doing here?

188
00:09:45,202 --> 00:09:47,502
Your Excellency.

189
00:09:47,817 --> 00:09:49,251
General Washington.

190
00:09:49,276 --> 00:09:52,276
<i>♪</i>

191
00:09:54,444 --> 00:09:57,412
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

192
00:09:57,454 --> 00:10:01,483
Synced and corrected by Aaronnmb
www. Addic7ed. Com

193
00:10:01,733 --> 00:10:03,384
Your Excellency?

194
00:10:03,425 --> 00:10:04,710
That's what they called him.

195
00:10:04,735 --> 00:10:06,717
He won't be president
for ten more years.

196
00:10:06,855 --> 00:10:09,590
I know I should be getting
used to all of this by now,

197
00:10:09,625 --> 00:10:11,459
but this one...

198
00:10:11,493 --> 00:10:14,128
What? That it's George Washington
or that he might want to kill us?

199
00:10:14,162 --> 00:10:16,998
Both. Maybe.

200
00:10:17,032 --> 00:10:18,317
I think both.

201
00:10:18,349 --> 00:10:19,582
[door creaks open]

202
00:10:22,285 --> 00:10:25,287
Easy, easy. I got a
man in the next room.

203
00:10:25,312 --> 00:10:27,642
If shots go off in here,
he shoots Washington.

204
00:10:27,676 --> 00:10:28,866
You're bluffing.

205
00:10:28,891 --> 00:10:30,778
You're talking to the
man who shot Lincoln.

206
00:10:30,812 --> 00:10:33,139
You really want to take that risk?

207
00:10:33,515 --> 00:10:36,255
Just put the gun away.

208
00:10:37,853 --> 00:10:40,177
I need your help.

209
00:10:41,026 --> 00:10:42,700
Our help?

210
00:10:43,492 --> 00:10:46,401
The gun? Please?

211
00:10:47,119 --> 00:10:49,353
You really want to risk
killing George Washington?

212
00:10:49,378 --> 00:10:51,111
- What the hell is this?
- When he comes in,

213
00:10:51,136 --> 00:10:53,729
just nod and follow my lead.

214
00:10:54,136 --> 00:10:57,983
Or else I'll have Washington
hang you for treason.

215
00:10:58,240 --> 00:10:59,674
Come on!

216
00:10:59,708 --> 00:11:00,987
Wyatt.

217
00:11:01,031 --> 00:11:02,112
[door creaking]

218
00:11:03,499 --> 00:11:04,961
Well...

219
00:11:07,849 --> 00:11:10,570
Are you who this man says you are?

220
00:11:12,500 --> 00:11:15,356
Well, that's a
complicated question, sir.

221
00:11:15,390 --> 00:11:18,703
Yes. Yes, we are.

222
00:11:18,728 --> 00:11:22,621
Mr. Roe here says you're the best
spies he's got in the Culper Ring.

223
00:11:22,646 --> 00:11:24,465
Yes, that's him.

224
00:11:24,499 --> 00:11:28,736
Mr. Austin Roe, the
renowned Prussian spy.

225
00:11:28,761 --> 00:11:30,769
Well, thank God for him.

226
00:11:31,406 --> 00:11:34,675
He's the one who warned
me about Arnold's betrayal,

227
00:11:34,710 --> 00:11:37,888
though the bastard still
slipped through our fingers.

228
00:11:37,913 --> 00:11:40,815
And you, you're a free man?

229
00:11:40,849 --> 00:11:44,051
And a hell of a spy.
I'm very unassuming.

230
00:11:44,086 --> 00:11:46,587
I'd like to tell them about the mission.

231
00:11:46,621 --> 00:11:47,650
The mission?

232
00:11:47,675 --> 00:11:49,861
The four of you are to
head into redcoat territory

233
00:11:49,886 --> 00:11:51,892
and capture Benedict Arnold.

234
00:11:51,927 --> 00:11:55,500
Say you were inspired
by Arnold's example.

235
00:11:55,897 --> 00:11:58,199
You'll find him and bring him back.

236
00:11:58,233 --> 00:12:00,063
To justice.

237
00:12:01,436 --> 00:12:02,770
Is there a problem?

238
00:12:02,804 --> 00:12:05,206
No, no, no. There's no problem.

239
00:12:05,240 --> 00:12:06,662
Right?

240
00:12:07,167 --> 00:12:09,358
No. No, sir.

241
00:12:10,217 --> 00:12:11,412
We'd be glad to help.

242
00:12:11,446 --> 00:12:14,795
Bring him to me. Alive.

243
00:12:15,317 --> 00:12:18,252
I want to look him in
the eye one last time...

244
00:12:18,286 --> 00:12:20,287
before I hang him.

245
00:12:22,324 --> 00:12:25,426
Why would Washington
believe you were a spy.

246
00:12:25,460 --> 00:12:28,062
Because even though George
Washington trusted Roe,

247
00:12:28,096 --> 00:12:29,964
they never actually met face - To - Face.

248
00:12:29,998 --> 00:12:33,267
So where is the real Austin Roe?

249
00:12:33,301 --> 00:12:35,603
- Dead in a ditch.
- You're a bastard.

250
00:12:35,637 --> 00:12:38,305
- What is all this, Flynn?
- I need Lucy.

251
00:12:39,041 --> 00:12:40,975
She'll know how to find Arnold.

252
00:12:41,009 --> 00:12:42,643
She knows everything about him.

253
00:12:42,677 --> 00:12:44,267
Why? So you can help him?

254
00:12:44,328 --> 00:12:46,362
Oh, I'm not gonna help Arnold.

255
00:12:46,387 --> 00:12:48,415
But I'm not taking him
back to Washington either.

256
00:12:48,450 --> 00:12:49,817
I'm gonna interrogate him,

257
00:12:49,851 --> 00:12:51,352
probably beat the hell out of him.

258
00:12:51,386 --> 00:12:53,421
Interrogate him? About what?

259
00:12:53,455 --> 00:12:57,458
That key from Bonnie and Clyde
opened an interesting door.

260
00:12:57,492 --> 00:12:59,385
Or clock.

261
00:12:59,895 --> 00:13:03,030
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

262
00:13:03,065 --> 00:13:06,065
<i>♪</i>

263
00:13:12,140 --> 00:13:15,076
- It's invisible ink.
- Read it.

264
00:13:17,546 --> 00:13:18,946
It's a letter Benedict Arnold wrote.

265
00:13:18,980 --> 00:13:22,110
It says something about
a Rittenhouse meeting.

266
00:13:22,135 --> 00:13:24,278
Are you telling me that Benedict Arnold

267
00:13:24,303 --> 00:13:25,475
was a member of Rittenhouse?

268
00:13:25,500 --> 00:13:28,956
Wasn't just a member.
He was a founding member.

269
00:13:28,990 --> 00:13:31,892
This is the year they
began. This is our chance.

270
00:13:31,927 --> 00:13:34,048
We're gonna kill
Rittenhouse in the crib.

271
00:13:34,073 --> 00:13:35,896
We're gonna stop them
before they ever get started.

272
00:13:35,931 --> 00:13:37,720
- We can't talk about this.
- You're gonna hunt these people down,

273
00:13:37,745 --> 00:13:39,915
- And you want us to help you?
- We can't talk about this.

274
00:13:39,940 --> 00:13:42,403
Why? Because of your
secret little recorder?

275
00:13:42,437 --> 00:13:44,505
What? You don't think I know?

276
00:13:44,539 --> 00:13:49,410
Okay, I'll make this easy.
You help me here, now,

277
00:13:49,444 --> 00:13:52,179
and I'll hand over the keys
to the Mothership, all yours.

278
00:13:52,214 --> 00:13:53,981
After all, once Rittenhouse is gone,

279
00:13:54,015 --> 00:13:55,983
why would I keep taking
these godforsaken trips?

280
00:13:56,017 --> 00:13:57,985
You're talking about killing
people, changing history.

281
00:13:58,019 --> 00:14:00,254
One last time and then it's over.

282
00:14:00,288 --> 00:14:02,423
That, or you keep chasing me,

283
00:14:02,457 --> 00:14:04,483
and I change history
a hundred more times.

284
00:14:04,508 --> 00:14:07,404
Or we can end this, Lucy, now,

285
00:14:07,429 --> 00:14:09,063
once and for all.

286
00:14:16,771 --> 00:14:18,362
Here.

287
00:14:18,387 --> 00:14:21,659
Your journal. Show of faith.

288
00:14:21,776 --> 00:14:23,911
See for yourself how bad
Rittenhouse really is.

289
00:14:23,945 --> 00:14:26,113
See in your own words.

290
00:14:29,317 --> 00:14:33,454
You're so full of crap,
it's coming out of your ears.

291
00:14:33,488 --> 00:14:36,524
We're not gonna help you, not
after everything we've been through.

292
00:14:36,558 --> 00:14:38,624
I figured you'd say that.

293
00:14:39,574 --> 00:14:41,842
So I'm sweetening the pot.

294
00:14:41,867 --> 00:14:44,132
You help me,

295
00:14:44,297 --> 00:14:48,569
and I'll tell you what happened
on Portero Road, mile marker 47.

296
00:14:49,437 --> 00:14:52,616
That's right, I'll give you
the name of your wife's killer.

297
00:14:57,812 --> 00:15:00,590
You have no idea who
could have done that.

298
00:15:00,615 --> 00:15:03,717
I'm not some local cop, Wyatt.

299
00:15:03,752 --> 00:15:06,220
I've still got some
friends in the right places.

300
00:15:06,254 --> 00:15:09,056
There was blood on the scene,
right, that wasn't Jessica's?

301
00:15:09,090 --> 00:15:12,179
That they never matched?
Well, I know whose it was.

302
00:15:13,138 --> 00:15:17,429
So you help me get Benedict Arnold,

303
00:15:18,133 --> 00:15:20,312
no more Rittenhouse.

304
00:15:21,440 --> 00:15:23,936
No more chasing me through time.

305
00:15:25,373 --> 00:15:28,364
Your wife's killer found.

306
00:15:30,111 --> 00:15:32,012
Everybody wins.

307
00:15:42,666 --> 00:15:45,134
Well, there goes recording.

308
00:15:45,169 --> 00:15:47,170
There's no amount of tampering
that is gonna hide the fact

309
00:15:47,195 --> 00:15:50,034
that we are helping
Flynn destroy Rittenhouse.

310
00:15:50,393 --> 00:15:52,141
My life is literally over.

311
00:15:52,176 --> 00:15:53,609
Not if we wipe them from the map.

312
00:15:53,644 --> 00:15:54,977
You're seriously considering this?

313
00:15:55,012 --> 00:15:56,546
Helping out a terrorist?

314
00:15:56,580 --> 00:15:58,915
That makes us a bunch of
Benedict Arnolds, you know that?

315
00:15:58,940 --> 00:16:01,673
- You've had better jokes.
- Well, I'm nervous.

316
00:16:02,555 --> 00:16:04,523
You can't tell me you
actually trust Flynn.

317
00:16:04,548 --> 00:16:08,351
No, of course not, but if
there is even a 1% chance

318
00:16:08,376 --> 00:16:11,236
that he really knows
who Jessica's killer is?

319
00:16:12,362 --> 00:16:14,030
Where do you come out on this?

320
00:16:14,064 --> 00:16:16,777
If this is true, Rittenhouse has
their fingerprints all over...

321
00:16:16,802 --> 00:16:18,849
the Trail of Tears, Jonestown Massacre,

322
00:16:18,874 --> 00:16:20,903
the Waco Siege, but
it's all still history,

323
00:16:20,938 --> 00:16:23,466
which is what we're supposed
to protect, even the bad stuff.

324
00:16:23,867 --> 00:16:25,401
Aren't we?

325
00:16:25,733 --> 00:16:28,768
- Everyone ready?
- Ready for what?

326
00:16:28,793 --> 00:16:30,513
There's a British Garrison up the road.

327
00:16:30,547 --> 00:16:31,857
We go defect.

328
00:16:31,882 --> 00:16:34,693
And why would the British
believe that we're defectors?

329
00:16:35,919 --> 00:16:38,888
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

330
00:16:38,922 --> 00:16:40,711
<i>♪</i>

331
00:16:40,751 --> 00:16:41,798
[gunfire]

332
00:16:41,823 --> 00:16:43,179
Do they have to make it look so real?

333
00:16:43,204 --> 00:16:44,227
Help! We're deserters!

334
00:16:44,261 --> 00:16:46,062
- Get ready!
- We're deserters!

335
00:16:46,096 --> 00:16:47,163
Don't shoot! Don't shoot!

336
00:16:47,197 --> 00:16:48,633
Get down! Fire!

337
00:16:48,658 --> 00:16:51,204
[gunfire]

338
00:16:51,229 --> 00:16:54,229
<i>♪</i>

339
00:17:15,243 --> 00:17:17,644
Okay, Lucy, you're up.

340
00:17:17,828 --> 00:17:21,222
General Arnold. You asked to see me.

341
00:17:21,774 --> 00:17:23,375
General Clinton sent us.

342
00:17:23,433 --> 00:17:24,777
We are loyalists, sir.

343
00:17:24,802 --> 00:17:26,941
- Inspired by your example.
- Is that so?

344
00:17:26,966 --> 00:17:28,925
We have covert information for you,

345
00:17:28,950 --> 00:17:31,378
about Washington's troop movements.

346
00:17:33,957 --> 00:17:36,005
I received no word from General Clinton.

347
00:17:36,030 --> 00:17:38,332
Clinton was supposed to send it.

348
00:17:41,285 --> 00:17:43,286
[whispering] Confidentially,

349
00:17:43,312 --> 00:17:47,113
you and I both know General
Clinton can be a bit... erratic.

350
00:17:47,651 --> 00:17:50,119
Perhaps a touch of his mother's lunacy.

351
00:17:50,419 --> 00:17:52,787
And you've met this man before.

352
00:17:52,829 --> 00:17:54,463
You fought with him at Ridgefield.

353
00:17:54,498 --> 00:17:56,972
He served under Colonel Lamb.

354
00:17:59,503 --> 00:18:02,171
Yes, that's right. I did.

355
00:18:02,206 --> 00:18:04,674
It's so good to see you again, sir.

356
00:18:04,708 --> 00:18:07,677
<i>[tense music]</i>

357
00:18:07,711 --> 00:18:10,711
<i>♪</i>

358
00:18:12,349 --> 00:18:15,851
Yes, I think I remember after all.

359
00:18:15,886 --> 00:18:18,154
Of course. [chuckles lightly]

360
00:18:18,188 --> 00:18:19,817
This way.

361
00:18:19,842 --> 00:18:22,856
<i>♪</i>

362
00:18:23,860 --> 00:18:25,661
[door rattles open]

363
00:18:26,239 --> 00:18:29,465
Let me introduce Earl Cornwallis.

364
00:18:29,499 --> 00:18:31,200
These are loyalists to the cause.

365
00:18:31,235 --> 00:18:32,544
Madam.

366
00:18:32,569 --> 00:18:34,481
They've come bearing gifts.

367
00:18:34,630 --> 00:18:37,340
So what's Washington's
plan for his troops?

368
00:18:37,374 --> 00:18:39,041
Could we speak in private, sir?

369
00:18:39,076 --> 00:18:41,877
These are trustworthy men.
Say what you've come to say.

370
00:18:41,912 --> 00:18:44,213
We've defected because
of your example, General.

371
00:18:44,248 --> 00:18:45,909
We'd prefer to speak only with you.

372
00:18:45,934 --> 00:18:48,113
Well, Madam, I'm not sure you're
in any place to make that decision.

373
00:18:48,138 --> 00:18:49,448
Come on!

374
00:18:49,841 --> 00:18:51,299
- [muffled gunshots]
- [gasps]

375
00:18:51,973 --> 00:18:53,369
What the hell?

376
00:18:53,871 --> 00:18:54,995
Stay away!

377
00:18:55,913 --> 00:18:58,981
- What the hell is going on?
- Managing the situation.

378
00:19:00,890 --> 00:19:02,824
You just killed Cornwallis.

379
00:19:02,849 --> 00:19:04,589
In 20 years, he's supposed to negotiate

380
00:19:04,614 --> 00:19:05,987
the peace treaty between
Britain and Napoleon.

381
00:19:06,012 --> 00:19:07,637
So history will find someone else.

382
00:19:07,671 --> 00:19:09,917
You see one redcoat, you've
seen them all. Big deal.

383
00:19:09,942 --> 00:19:12,081
It's a very big deal.

384
00:19:12,609 --> 00:19:14,377
Rufus, the curtains.

385
00:19:14,411 --> 00:19:16,768
I gotta find a place to
hide the bodies, quick.

386
00:19:21,184 --> 00:19:23,212
You're Washington's men?

387
00:19:23,237 --> 00:19:26,493
No, no, no. Washington's
men never find you.

388
00:19:26,556 --> 00:19:29,275
Actually, you're meant
to get away scot - Free,

389
00:19:29,300 --> 00:19:31,370
live a comfortable life in England.

390
00:19:31,395 --> 00:19:33,126
Then who are you?

391
00:19:34,098 --> 00:19:35,579
Honestly?

392
00:19:36,884 --> 00:19:39,919
We're, uh, time travelers
from the year 2016

393
00:19:39,944 --> 00:19:42,407
who came all the way
here just to meet you.

394
00:19:46,810 --> 00:19:50,140
[laughing]

395
00:19:50,873 --> 00:19:52,774
- You're mad.
- Yeah.

396
00:19:52,816 --> 00:19:53,999
It doesn't matter who we are.

397
00:19:54,024 --> 00:19:56,768
What matters is what we need to know...

398
00:19:56,793 --> 00:19:58,749
about Rittenhouse.

399
00:20:00,979 --> 00:20:03,468
I don't know what you're talking about.

400
00:20:09,132 --> 00:20:11,334
This is your handwriting, Isn't it?

401
00:20:14,671 --> 00:20:18,708
"Today I met some gentlemen
with a great vision for America.

402
00:20:18,742 --> 00:20:20,476
"Rittenhouse.

403
00:20:20,510 --> 00:20:23,776
"They're recruiting worthy
men and have sought me out."

404
00:20:25,616 --> 00:20:27,529
I never wrote that.

405
00:20:27,851 --> 00:20:30,152
Maybe we could help you remember.

406
00:20:30,187 --> 00:20:32,988
Beat me to death, have
Washington hang me.

407
00:20:33,023 --> 00:20:34,873
I don't know what you're talking about.

408
00:20:34,898 --> 00:20:38,810
I understand, understand why
you would betray Washington,

409
00:20:38,862 --> 00:20:40,129
why you would go to Rittenhouse.

410
00:20:40,163 --> 00:20:42,164
You must know me well.

411
00:20:42,199 --> 00:20:45,568
<i>[pensive music]</i>

412
00:20:45,602 --> 00:20:47,553
Well, I...

413
00:20:47,654 --> 00:20:51,440
I know you sank your entire
fortune into the Patriot cause.

414
00:20:51,475 --> 00:20:55,032
I know that you were one of
Washington's best and brightest.

415
00:20:55,097 --> 00:20:57,131
At Saratoga,

416
00:20:57,447 --> 00:20:59,582
when they shot your horse
dead right from underneath you,

417
00:20:59,616 --> 00:21:01,016
you kept fighting.

418
00:21:01,051 --> 00:21:04,891
And when a musket ball
shattered your leg,

419
00:21:04,916 --> 00:21:06,264
what did you do? You kept fighting.

420
00:21:06,289 --> 00:21:07,806
What of it?

421
00:21:08,125 --> 00:21:10,346
But when it came time...

422
00:21:10,371 --> 00:21:11,927
[sighs]

423
00:21:11,962 --> 00:21:15,297
for your promotion to Major General,

424
00:21:15,332 --> 00:21:17,971
the promotion that you earned,

425
00:21:18,235 --> 00:21:21,670
congress just passed
you over, didn't they?

426
00:21:21,705 --> 00:21:23,305
[chuckles]

427
00:21:23,340 --> 00:21:26,518
And what did Washington do for you?

428
00:21:29,182 --> 00:21:30,582
Nothing.

429
00:21:34,084 --> 00:21:35,671
And so, uh,

430
00:21:37,312 --> 00:21:41,557
you betrayed him, you betrayed
everything that you once believed in.

431
00:21:41,591 --> 00:21:43,187
But for what?

432
00:21:43,992 --> 00:21:45,027
Pride?

433
00:21:45,061 --> 00:21:47,375
He betrayed me.

434
00:21:48,218 --> 00:21:50,332
He was my brother,

435
00:21:50,367 --> 00:21:52,656
and he abandoned me.

436
00:21:53,608 --> 00:21:55,663
But Rittenhouse,

437
00:21:56,072 --> 00:21:58,707
he's gonna give me the
future that I deserve.

438
00:21:58,742 --> 00:22:03,218
And no one, not you,
not anyone, will stop us.

439
00:22:03,265 --> 00:22:05,815
Wait. Did you just say "he"?

440
00:22:05,849 --> 00:22:08,085
The man you're asking
about, David Rittenhouse.

441
00:22:08,110 --> 00:22:10,390
Rittenhouse isn't a
they, It's one person?

442
00:22:10,415 --> 00:22:13,601
He has more followers
every day, but yes.

443
00:22:15,392 --> 00:22:17,515
[whispering] Did you know about this?

444
00:22:17,968 --> 00:22:19,695
- That it was just one man?
- No.

445
00:22:19,720 --> 00:22:23,032
It wasn't anywhere. I - It
wasn't in the journal.

446
00:22:23,066 --> 00:22:26,585
What journal? What
are you talking about?

447
00:22:29,739 --> 00:22:31,919
Introduce us to him.

448
00:22:32,576 --> 00:22:35,678
A woman? A negro?

449
00:22:35,712 --> 00:22:37,746
You're insane.

450
00:22:37,781 --> 00:22:39,802
He'd see her in his bed
and him in the fields.

451
00:22:39,827 --> 00:22:42,263
You will introduce us to him.

452
00:22:42,686 --> 00:22:45,454
And why would I ever do that?

453
00:22:48,291 --> 00:22:51,527
Washington's holding your wife prisoner.

454
00:22:51,552 --> 00:22:54,585
If we haven't returned
with you in three days,

455
00:22:54,611 --> 00:22:57,891
he will execute her for your treason.

456
00:23:02,272 --> 00:23:05,875
So take us to Rittenhouse,
and save your wife.

457
00:23:05,909 --> 00:23:09,044
<i>[pensive music]</i>

458
00:23:09,079 --> 00:23:12,047
The things we all do for love.

459
00:23:12,082 --> 00:23:15,082
<i>♪</i>

460
00:23:19,901 --> 00:23:22,068
Okay, Arnold and Flynn
will be down any second.

461
00:23:22,093 --> 00:23:23,792
What do we think?

462
00:23:25,080 --> 00:23:26,683
I'm in.

463
00:23:27,761 --> 00:23:30,113
You were the one that said we
were a bunch of Benedict Arnolds.

464
00:23:30,138 --> 00:23:32,480
That was before Rittenhouse
was just one dude.

465
00:23:32,613 --> 00:23:34,455
If all we gotta do is stop one guy...

466
00:23:34,480 --> 00:23:36,216
What? So we just kill him?

467
00:23:36,371 --> 00:23:38,218
We just kill him in cold blood?

468
00:23:38,252 --> 00:23:40,238
Wyatt's killed before.

469
00:23:41,417 --> 00:23:42,989
So have I.

470
00:23:43,441 --> 00:23:47,127
If this one move cuts
the head off the snake,

471
00:23:47,410 --> 00:23:50,312
wipes Rittenhouse out,
frees me from them,

472
00:23:50,337 --> 00:23:52,938
frees my family, then my vote...

473
00:23:55,774 --> 00:23:57,542
my vote is yes.

474
00:23:57,576 --> 00:23:59,383
I vote yes too.

475
00:24:05,859 --> 00:24:08,701
If we do this, then
history's gonna change.

476
00:24:08,726 --> 00:24:10,922
And what if... what if more
people vanish like my sister?

477
00:24:10,956 --> 00:24:12,757
What if more people are saved?

478
00:24:12,791 --> 00:24:17,228
Hell, what if you come home to Amy?

479
00:24:21,967 --> 00:24:23,512
Lucy,

480
00:24:24,178 --> 00:24:27,776
this isn't saving the
Moon launch or the Alamo.

481
00:24:27,801 --> 00:24:31,943
This is killing one evil son of a bitch,

482
00:24:31,977 --> 00:24:35,635
to save maybe hundreds of lives.

483
00:24:35,660 --> 00:24:38,249
I'm sorry, I don't think
that "history" is an excuse

484
00:24:38,283 --> 00:24:40,895
to sit back and let people suffer.

485
00:24:42,654 --> 00:24:45,390
I know you well enough by now.

486
00:24:45,424 --> 00:24:49,223
What you really believe
in is helping people.

487
00:24:50,996 --> 00:24:54,727
But, hey, we're in this together, so...

488
00:24:55,567 --> 00:24:58,665
So are we all ready to do this?

489
00:24:59,972 --> 00:25:02,743
Lucy, are we ready?

490
00:25:02,768 --> 00:25:05,157
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

491
00:25:05,182 --> 00:25:06,454
Yeah.

492
00:25:06,512 --> 00:25:09,512
<i>♪</i>

493
00:25:20,976 --> 00:25:22,791
Whoa.

494
00:25:26,198 --> 00:25:28,466
Horses need water.

495
00:25:28,500 --> 00:25:30,001
And I could use a thunder mug.

496
00:25:30,035 --> 00:25:31,544
Sounds amazing. Me too.

497
00:25:31,569 --> 00:25:33,337
What do you drink in a thunder mug?

498
00:25:33,372 --> 00:25:35,280
You urinate into it.

499
00:25:35,305 --> 00:25:38,468
Right, of course. Totally knew that.

500
00:25:39,978 --> 00:25:42,978
<i>♪</i>

501
00:25:57,624 --> 00:26:00,523
Hey, buddy. Hey.

502
00:26:01,200 --> 00:26:03,201
Hey, buddy.

503
00:26:10,142 --> 00:26:12,477
You know about horses?

504
00:26:12,511 --> 00:26:15,221
I wanted to be a cowboy growing up.

505
00:26:16,148 --> 00:26:20,768
You ever heard of,
uh, Tex Willer comics?

506
00:26:20,793 --> 00:26:23,120
He had a horse named Dynamite.

507
00:26:23,155 --> 00:26:26,351
They protected the good
guys against the bad guys.

508
00:26:31,363 --> 00:26:34,632
I hate to be a told - You - So, but, um,

509
00:26:34,666 --> 00:26:37,969
the journal did say something
about you and me working together?

510
00:26:38,003 --> 00:26:40,482
- Don't push your luck.
- Fair enough.

511
00:26:43,075 --> 00:26:44,943
Say we do this.

512
00:26:45,711 --> 00:26:47,717
That we really...

513
00:26:48,080 --> 00:26:50,177
take out Rittenhouse.

514
00:26:52,518 --> 00:26:54,638
Then what will you do?

515
00:26:55,554 --> 00:26:57,822
Go home to my family.

516
00:26:57,856 --> 00:26:59,982
They'll be alive again.

517
00:27:01,293 --> 00:27:04,195
Let my little girl jump into my arms.

518
00:27:04,229 --> 00:27:06,230
Hug my wife.

519
00:27:08,767 --> 00:27:11,168
And then say good - Bye
and walk away forever.

520
00:27:11,203 --> 00:27:12,697
What?

521
00:27:14,306 --> 00:27:16,384
You would just...

522
00:27:16,808 --> 00:27:19,110
you would just leave them after
all that we've been through?

523
00:27:19,144 --> 00:27:21,345
Chasing Rittenhouse,

524
00:27:21,380 --> 00:27:23,876
i've done horrible things...

525
00:27:25,157 --> 00:27:27,418
become something else.

526
00:27:27,452 --> 00:27:30,132
How can I bring that into my home?

527
00:27:32,090 --> 00:27:34,191
What kind of husband or...

528
00:27:34,226 --> 00:27:37,421
or a father can I be
after what I've done?

529
00:27:39,473 --> 00:27:41,728
We should keep moving.

530
00:27:43,468 --> 00:27:46,437
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

531
00:27:46,471 --> 00:27:49,471
<i>♪</i>

532
00:28:02,821 --> 00:28:04,789
Where'd you get a spyglass like that?

533
00:28:04,823 --> 00:28:07,063
I told you. The future.

534
00:28:12,380 --> 00:28:13,781
Those men know you?

535
00:28:13,806 --> 00:28:15,442
I'll introduce you as volunteers,

536
00:28:15,467 --> 00:28:16,968
tell Rittenhouse you're patriots

537
00:28:17,002 --> 00:28:19,874
who've lost faith in the cause like me.

538
00:28:21,506 --> 00:28:24,631
But I suggest we don't
bring everyone to the party.

539
00:28:25,777 --> 00:28:29,076
These are idiotic, unenlightened times,

540
00:28:29,572 --> 00:28:31,474
but I understand.

541
00:28:32,265 --> 00:28:34,343
We'll leave Rufus behind.

542
00:28:34,534 --> 00:28:37,502
<i>[foreboding music]</i>

543
00:28:37,527 --> 00:28:40,527
<i>♪</i>

544
00:28:55,812 --> 00:28:57,412
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

545
00:28:57,437 --> 00:29:00,437
<i>♪</i>

546
00:29:09,891 --> 00:29:12,167
[clocks ticking]

547
00:29:13,328 --> 00:29:16,148
[clocks chiming]

548
00:29:17,742 --> 00:29:19,679
[doors creaking]

549
00:29:20,779 --> 00:29:23,180
- General Arnold.
- John.

550
00:29:23,215 --> 00:29:26,031
- Is Father expecting you?
- Is he home?

551
00:29:26,056 --> 00:29:28,179
I'd like him to meet my
friends. They want to join.

552
00:29:28,204 --> 00:29:30,336
- Lot of clocks.
- Father made them.

553
00:29:30,361 --> 00:29:32,262
He's teaching me to make them too.

554
00:29:32,390 --> 00:29:34,725
- He's fascinated with time.
- Hmm.

555
00:29:34,759 --> 00:29:37,467
- Is your father here, John?
- Do you want to help us?

556
00:29:37,492 --> 00:29:39,396
Is that why you're here?

557
00:29:39,431 --> 00:29:41,265
This is a conversation
for your father, John.

558
00:29:41,299 --> 00:29:44,435
[clocks ticking]

559
00:29:55,413 --> 00:29:57,381
Is that your clock?

560
00:29:57,415 --> 00:30:01,008
Yes, but I can't seem to get
the ratchet wheel to work.

561
00:30:01,033 --> 00:30:03,942
Father says I'm not
paying enough attention.

562
00:30:10,362 --> 00:30:12,459
Looks like you're doing a fine job.

563
00:30:12,484 --> 00:30:13,964
It's a beautiful clock.

564
00:30:13,999 --> 00:30:17,452
My father says that peasants
are like the hands of a clock.

565
00:30:17,477 --> 00:30:19,788
Around and around they go.

566
00:30:21,609 --> 00:30:22,740
What does that mean?

567
00:30:22,774 --> 00:30:25,409
Because a peasant is no more
capable of choosing his own path

568
00:30:25,443 --> 00:30:27,155
than the hands of a clock.

569
00:30:28,812 --> 00:30:30,046
Well...

570
00:30:30,454 --> 00:30:32,537
who chooses the path for them?

571
00:30:32,562 --> 00:30:34,632
The clockmaker, of course.

572
00:30:36,155 --> 00:30:41,046
And are the members of
Rittenhouse the clockmakers?

573
00:30:42,131 --> 00:30:43,699
No one else can do it.

574
00:30:43,921 --> 00:30:45,763
Father says monarchies are too selfish

575
00:30:45,797 --> 00:30:48,599
and democracies are too chaotic.

576
00:30:48,633 --> 00:30:51,302
So the members of
Rittenhouse are not part of,

577
00:30:51,336 --> 00:30:53,370
you know, any government?

578
00:30:53,405 --> 00:30:56,807
Not necessarily. Control
is all that matters.

579
00:30:56,841 --> 00:30:59,710
Usually it's best
exercised from the shadows.

580
00:30:59,744 --> 00:31:03,847
[clocks ticking]

581
00:31:03,882 --> 00:31:05,716
What about the people that want a voice

582
00:31:05,750 --> 00:31:07,117
in how they're controlled?

583
00:31:07,152 --> 00:31:08,719
Peasants can't govern themselves

584
00:31:08,753 --> 00:31:10,654
any more than ants can rule the jungle.

585
00:31:10,689 --> 00:31:13,974
Most peasants want nothing more
than the illusion of a voice.

586
00:31:13,999 --> 00:31:16,671
Father says that's what democracy's for.

587
00:31:16,718 --> 00:31:18,138
Oh.

588
00:31:18,163 --> 00:31:22,333
<i>[tense music]</i>

589
00:31:22,367 --> 00:31:26,637
What you're describing sounds like
tyranny disguised as democracy.

590
00:31:26,671 --> 00:31:29,373
Father believes there's no other choice.

591
00:31:29,407 --> 00:31:32,076
<i>♪</i>

592
00:31:32,110 --> 00:31:34,011
What do you believe, John?

593
00:31:34,045 --> 00:31:37,045
<i>♪</i>

594
00:31:38,283 --> 00:31:40,985
No one's ever asked me that before.

595
00:31:41,019 --> 00:31:43,220
[clocks ticking]

596
00:31:43,254 --> 00:31:45,089
[door clicking and creaking open]

597
00:31:45,123 --> 00:31:47,257
Benedict Arnold.

598
00:31:47,292 --> 00:31:50,173
You honor us with your presence.

599
00:31:51,908 --> 00:31:53,767
Father.

600
00:31:54,415 --> 00:31:56,040
That's him.

601
00:31:57,439 --> 00:31:59,236
David, you look well.

602
00:31:59,270 --> 00:32:01,005
John was just telling
my friends about you.

603
00:32:01,039 --> 00:32:03,205
Yes, Father. They want to join.

604
00:32:03,942 --> 00:32:05,736
They do?

605
00:32:06,431 --> 00:32:09,305
You've never brought me
recruits before, Benedict.

606
00:32:09,330 --> 00:32:11,782
<i>[foreboding music]</i>

607
00:32:11,816 --> 00:32:14,385
May I get a better look at you?

608
00:32:14,419 --> 00:32:17,228
My eyes aren't what they used to be.

609
00:32:19,189 --> 00:32:22,189
Go on. Father wants to examine you.

610
00:32:22,627 --> 00:32:25,627
<i>♪</i>

611
00:32:32,103 --> 00:32:34,747
You have good, strong teeth.

612
00:32:35,507 --> 00:32:38,142
- Good skull proportion.
- Stop.

613
00:32:38,176 --> 00:32:41,245
Your hips are a bit narrow,
but nobody's perfect.

614
00:32:41,279 --> 00:32:44,214
Have you reproduced yet?

615
00:32:46,221 --> 00:32:48,643
- No.
- Good.

616
00:32:49,854 --> 00:32:51,347
[gasps]

617
00:32:51,372 --> 00:32:52,589
Wyatt.

618
00:32:52,614 --> 00:32:53,659
What are you doing?

619
00:32:53,684 --> 00:32:55,402
No sudden movements, If you please.

620
00:32:55,427 --> 00:32:57,345
David, what is this?

621
00:32:57,370 --> 00:32:58,896
These men are here to kill me.

622
00:32:58,930 --> 00:33:02,018
- You got this all wrong.
- Really?

623
00:33:02,600 --> 00:33:04,968
The sweat on her brow.

624
00:33:05,065 --> 00:33:08,790
The hand near your pocket,
where I assume you have a pistol.

625
00:33:08,815 --> 00:33:12,876
This isn't the first time I've seen
that look on a man's face, believe me.

626
00:33:12,901 --> 00:33:14,940
You mean me harm.

627
00:33:15,947 --> 00:33:17,981
But don't worry, my dear.

628
00:33:18,016 --> 00:33:21,143
We'll still find a good use for you.

629
00:33:21,186 --> 00:33:23,287
<i>[ominous music]</i>

630
00:33:23,321 --> 00:33:26,323
[indistinct chatter]

631
00:33:32,697 --> 00:33:35,666
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

632
00:33:35,700 --> 00:33:39,837
<i>♪</i>

633
00:33:39,871 --> 00:33:43,114
[coughing]

634
00:33:43,418 --> 00:33:47,654
<i>♪</i>

635
00:33:47,679 --> 00:33:49,278
Get up.

636
00:33:50,014 --> 00:33:52,015
Boy, get up.

637
00:33:54,052 --> 00:33:56,019
- I said get up.
- [grunting]

638
00:33:56,054 --> 00:33:58,122
[all gasp]

639
00:33:58,156 --> 00:34:01,164
<i>♪</i>

640
00:34:04,620 --> 00:34:07,622
[clocks ticking]

641
00:34:11,354 --> 00:34:13,747
What an ingenious pistol.

642
00:34:14,693 --> 00:34:16,807
I've never seen its equal.

643
00:34:16,841 --> 00:34:18,742
You have to believe me, David.

644
00:34:18,777 --> 00:34:21,145
How could I have known
they were lying to me?

645
00:34:21,179 --> 00:34:23,426
You know all I ever want
is to be of service to you,

646
00:34:23,451 --> 00:34:25,549
to serve the cause.

647
00:34:25,583 --> 00:34:28,404
- I'm so grateful for the opp...
- Shut up, Benedict.

648
00:34:29,354 --> 00:34:30,990
I'm sorry, sir.

649
00:34:32,423 --> 00:34:35,982
Did he tell you how I
admire his military genius?

650
00:34:36,561 --> 00:34:39,329
How when the war is over, I
will give him a place near me

651
00:34:39,364 --> 00:34:40,664
at the table of elders?

652
00:34:40,698 --> 00:34:42,599
I'm honored, sir.

653
00:34:42,634 --> 00:34:46,266
But did he also tell you
about his alcoholic father?

654
00:34:47,641 --> 00:34:49,940
His poor education?

655
00:34:49,974 --> 00:34:52,176
His vanity?

656
00:34:52,210 --> 00:34:54,778
- His bad temper? His...
- David, please.

657
00:34:54,813 --> 00:34:57,212
After everything I've done for you?

658
00:34:58,550 --> 00:35:01,451
You're an idiot, Benedict.

659
00:35:01,486 --> 00:35:05,236
So blinded by your wounded pride...

660
00:35:06,751 --> 00:35:11,228
that you brought these people
into my house to kill me.

661
00:35:11,485 --> 00:35:14,965
It was just a mistake, sir.
Please. You can trust me.

662
00:35:14,999 --> 00:35:17,434
You betrayed your best
friend in the whole world,

663
00:35:17,468 --> 00:35:19,836
so why would I ever trust you?

664
00:35:20,500 --> 00:35:21,956
[gunshot]

665
00:35:23,073 --> 00:35:26,713
[gunshots]

666
00:35:30,534 --> 00:35:33,468
<i>[ominous music]</i>

667
00:35:33,503 --> 00:35:36,503
<i>♪</i>

668
00:35:38,784 --> 00:35:40,948
Where did you get this?

669
00:35:42,488 --> 00:35:44,182
No, no.

670
00:35:44,523 --> 00:35:46,424
Don't worry.

671
00:35:46,459 --> 00:35:48,416
I'm a clockmaker.

672
00:35:48,441 --> 00:35:50,510
I'll figure it out.

673
00:35:53,366 --> 00:35:55,967
- Son?
- Yes, Father?

674
00:35:56,002 --> 00:35:59,170
Watch. It's important that you see this.

675
00:36:03,774 --> 00:36:05,009
No!

676
00:36:09,385 --> 00:36:10,949
Please don't hurt them in front of me.

677
00:36:10,983 --> 00:36:14,486
Now, John, what have I
said about seeing the world

678
00:36:14,520 --> 00:36:16,526
as it really is?

679
00:36:17,554 --> 00:36:19,143
Yes, Father.

680
00:36:21,327 --> 00:36:23,752
You two are sentenced to death.

681
00:36:24,196 --> 00:36:26,031
But you...

682
00:36:26,065 --> 00:36:28,838
are to be brought to my bedchamber

683
00:36:28,863 --> 00:36:31,863
<i>♪</i>

684
00:36:40,238 --> 00:36:41,239
Hey!

685
00:36:41,272 --> 00:36:42,528
[gunshot]

686
00:36:43,079 --> 00:36:45,630
[all grunting]

687
00:36:45,655 --> 00:36:48,624
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

688
00:36:48,649 --> 00:36:50,419
<i>♪</i>

689
00:36:50,443 --> 00:36:51,443
Flynn!

690
00:36:51,457 --> 00:36:52,528
[gunshot]

691
00:36:53,859 --> 00:36:56,859
<i>♪</i>

692
00:37:05,738 --> 00:37:08,073
[both panting]

693
00:37:08,107 --> 00:37:11,843
[clocks ticking]

694
00:37:11,877 --> 00:37:14,212
<i>[tense music]</i>

695
00:37:14,246 --> 00:37:16,181
[gunshot]

696
00:37:16,215 --> 00:37:20,352
<i>♪</i>

697
00:37:20,551 --> 00:37:23,121
Killing me won't change anything.

698
00:37:23,155 --> 00:37:24,786
There are others.

699
00:37:25,157 --> 00:37:27,262
This will outlive me...

700
00:37:27,287 --> 00:37:29,137
you...

701
00:37:29,591 --> 00:37:31,520
all of us.

702
00:37:32,747 --> 00:37:34,272
Rittenhouse will become...

703
00:37:34,297 --> 00:37:35,697
[gunshot]

704
00:37:40,573 --> 00:37:42,206
You did it.

705
00:37:43,509 --> 00:37:45,410
You actually did it.

706
00:37:45,444 --> 00:37:48,446
[clocks ticking]

707
00:37:52,197 --> 00:37:53,965
[sighs]

708
00:37:53,990 --> 00:37:56,025
Where's the boy?

709
00:37:58,157 --> 00:38:00,624
What... the... the boy?
What do you mean the boy?

710
00:38:00,649 --> 00:38:02,413
The boy's gone.

711
00:38:02,898 --> 00:38:05,163
His son, he escaped.

712
00:38:05,197 --> 00:38:06,731
Are you saying that you
want to kill his son?

713
00:38:06,766 --> 00:38:08,800
I don't want to, but we need to.

714
00:38:08,834 --> 00:38:10,757
You heard; he believes the
same things as his father.

715
00:38:10,782 --> 00:38:13,584
You already killed Rittenhouse.
There's no need to kill the boy.

716
00:38:13,773 --> 00:38:16,265
<i>[tense music]</i>

717
00:38:16,290 --> 00:38:17,976
<i>♪</i>

718
00:38:18,010 --> 00:38:19,677
Flynn.

719
00:38:19,712 --> 00:38:21,813
<i>♪</i>

720
00:38:21,847 --> 00:38:23,448
Flynn.

721
00:38:23,482 --> 00:38:25,101
Flynn!

722
00:38:25,126 --> 00:38:26,702
Guys, help me out!

723
00:38:26,727 --> 00:38:29,696
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

724
00:38:29,721 --> 00:38:32,423
<i>♪</i>

725
00:38:32,691 --> 00:38:36,494
You guys find Flynn,
i'll go find the boy.

726
00:38:36,529 --> 00:38:39,529
<i>♪</i>

727
00:38:50,800 --> 00:38:52,119
No, no.

728
00:38:52,144 --> 00:38:54,612
[sobbing] No, please don't kill me.

729
00:38:54,647 --> 00:38:58,716
Please. Please. Please don't kill me.

730
00:38:58,751 --> 00:39:01,019
No. No, no, no. Don't kill me.

731
00:39:01,053 --> 00:39:03,596
Please! Please don't!

732
00:39:03,989 --> 00:39:05,659
Please!

733
00:39:06,618 --> 00:39:08,260
Please.

734
00:39:10,952 --> 00:39:12,880
[whispers] Don't do it.

735
00:39:13,532 --> 00:39:16,201
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

736
00:39:16,235 --> 00:39:18,336
[groans]

737
00:39:18,370 --> 00:39:20,171
<i>♪</i>

738
00:39:20,206 --> 00:39:23,174
[breathing sharply]

739
00:39:23,209 --> 00:39:26,209
<i>♪</i>

740
00:39:33,119 --> 00:39:35,520
[sighs]

741
00:39:35,554 --> 00:39:38,790
- Move.
- No.

742
00:39:39,152 --> 00:39:41,257
- Move!
- No!

743
00:39:42,638 --> 00:39:44,205
I'm not letting you kill a child.

744
00:39:44,230 --> 00:39:47,566
He's all that's left of Rittenhouse.

745
00:39:47,591 --> 00:39:49,375
You don't know that.

746
00:39:49,709 --> 00:39:51,443
He said that there were others.

747
00:39:51,468 --> 00:39:53,981
You don't know that killing
his son will change anything.

748
00:39:54,006 --> 00:39:56,375
He wants everything his father wants.

749
00:39:56,400 --> 00:39:59,117
When you were 12, you
wanted to be a cowboy.

750
00:40:00,146 --> 00:40:02,881
- People change.
- He's gonna do terrible things!

751
00:40:02,907 --> 00:40:04,574
Why?

752
00:40:04,617 --> 00:40:07,078
Because his father wants him to?

753
00:40:07,653 --> 00:40:09,481
You don't know that!

754
00:40:09,630 --> 00:40:12,265
You have a choice right now!

755
00:40:12,872 --> 00:40:16,161
We all have choices! We can decide...

756
00:40:16,795 --> 00:40:19,230
we can decide to be something different.

757
00:40:19,265 --> 00:40:22,233
<i>[pensive music]</i>

758
00:40:22,268 --> 00:40:25,937
<i>♪</i>

759
00:40:25,971 --> 00:40:28,242
Please, no, please.

760
00:40:28,484 --> 00:40:30,775
Please don't do this, please.

761
00:40:30,809 --> 00:40:32,810
Please.

762
00:40:32,845 --> 00:40:35,747
You... you said... you said
that you couldn't be a father

763
00:40:35,781 --> 00:40:37,815
after what you've done.

764
00:40:37,850 --> 00:40:40,518
But you can, okay? You can.

765
00:40:40,553 --> 00:40:42,487
You can go back, but not if you do this.

766
00:40:42,521 --> 00:40:44,122
- Please, please!
- Get out of my way.

767
00:40:44,179 --> 00:40:47,179
<i>♪</i>

768
00:40:50,329 --> 00:40:52,297
[sobbing]

769
00:40:52,331 --> 00:40:53,635
John?

770
00:40:54,733 --> 00:40:56,601
John!

771
00:40:56,635 --> 00:41:00,505
<i>♪</i>

772
00:41:00,539 --> 00:41:02,540
He's gone.

773
00:41:04,710 --> 00:41:06,177
- Come here!
- What?

774
00:41:06,212 --> 00:41:07,979
No. Where are you taking me?

775
00:41:08,013 --> 00:41:10,783
I thought you understood
what was at stake.

776
00:41:10,808 --> 00:41:12,375
Come here!

777
00:41:12,400 --> 00:41:13,713
<i>[ominous music]</i>

778
00:41:13,738 --> 00:41:15,229
- Anything?
- No, you?

779
00:41:15,254 --> 00:41:17,377
- Nothing.
- Wyatt!

780
00:41:17,723 --> 00:41:19,619
- Wyatt!
- Come on.

781
00:41:20,088 --> 00:41:22,024
- Lucy!
- Wyatt!

782
00:41:22,049 --> 00:41:24,549
- Flynn!
- Rufus!

783
00:41:25,664 --> 00:41:28,566
No. No!

784
00:41:28,601 --> 00:41:30,735
- Let go of me!
- Lucy!

785
00:41:30,769 --> 00:41:32,510
Wyatt!

786
00:41:33,939 --> 00:41:35,729
Lucy!

787
00:41:35,754 --> 00:41:38,223
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

788
00:41:38,377 --> 00:41:40,345
